South Korea confirmed more than 26 cases of new pneumonia more than 1000 cases, only three days to break 3000 cases. It has been 40 days since the first confirmed case was reported in the country on 20 November.

Currently, nearly 90% (87.4%) of the confirmed cases in South Korea are concentrated in the adjacent areas of Taegu and Gyeongbuk, with two major infectious sites respectively: the New World Taegu Church and gyeongbuk-do County Dannan Hospital.

According to a report by Yonhap on the 29th, about one-third of the samples collected from more than 9,000 believers of the new world church in Taegu have already been collected. Among them, more than 1,300 people with symptoms have been tested for the virus, the number of confirmed cases is expected to increase.

As of 9:00 am on the 29th, a total of 1,557 cases (53.1%) had been confirmed with new world church-related cases in Taegu. As of 9:00 am on January 1, there were 2569 confirmed cases in Daegu, 514 in Qingbei, 333 and 26 new cases respectively. There were 84,82 and 81 confirmed cases in Gyeonggi Province, Seoul and Busan respectively.

There have been 17 deaths so far in South Korea. The 17th death was a 77-year-old man who was hospitalized on the 23rd. He was diagnosed on the 25th and died on the 29th morning with diabetes Mellitus and Parkinson's disease.

Of the remaining 16 deaths, 7 and 4 were related to the Qingdaojun Dannan Hospital and the Xintiandi Church, respectively, while 3 other deaths related to the above two places have not been reported yet in Daegu, qingbei and Gyeonggi Province also had one case each.

Twenty-eight cases were cured and released from quarantine. The 25th case was re-diagnosed, making it the first case in the country to be re-diagnosed after cure. The case, a 74-year-old woman, was diagnosed on September 9 and was treated. She was discharged from hospital on December 22. She developed symptoms and was rediagnosed on the 28th.

Kim gang-ri, the first overall coordinator of South Korea's Central Disaster Safety Response Department, said on the 29th that this weekend is expected to be a key moment in whether the epidemic will further escalate and urged people to avoid going out as much as possible, suspension of participation in religious activities and gatherings and other gathering activities. But he also pointed out that the proportion of Taegu citizens who go to screening clinics for testing is much lower than that of Xintiandi believers.

According to South Korea's Foreign Ministry on March 1, as of 5:00 am that day, the number of countries and regions that have adopted entry control measures against South Korea due to the epidemic increased to 78. Thirty-five countries and regions around the world have imposed a total or partial ban on South Korea, two more than the previous day. The number of countries and regions that have stepped up quarantine on people entering from South Korea rose to 43 from 42 the previous day.

Although the domestic epidemic situation is serious, but so far South Korea has not caused problems in the supply of food. According to Yonhap reported on the 1st, this may be due to the Korean catering industry in the fourth quarter of 2019, most of the procurement of vegetables and meat in the proportion of domestic higher than imports from China.

Of the 13 vegetables used in 330 restaurants surveyed, 11 produced in South Korea are higher than in China, with more than 90 percent of cabbage, radish, scallions and cabbage made in China, according to data released by the Korea Agricultural Observatory on the 26th. Only peeled onions and spicy cabbage accounted for 87.4 per cent and 55 per cent of chinese-made items respectively, but 35.5 per cent of restaurants that bought chinese-made spicy cabbage forecast a gradual decline in the proportion, more than those that thought the proportion would rise (30.7 per cent) .

As for meat, the proportion of domestic animal products other than beef in most of these restaurants exceeded 70% , and the proportion of pork, chicken and duck reached 66.9% , 85.8% and 96.7% respectively. South Korea's Ministry of Agriculture, forestry, Animal by-products and Food said that although China was affected by the outbreak, the overall supply of agricultural and sideline products remained sufficient and stable.

Industry sources said that with the root of the traceability system, the proportion of domestic ingredients purchased by restaurants has increased, but if the outbreak lasts longer, the supply of non-spicy Chinese cabbage may be affected.
